Original

The original data visualisation selected for the assignment was as follows:


Source: Visual Capitalist (2023).


Objective and Audience

The objective and audience of the original data visualisation chosen can be summarised as follows:

Objective The original data visualisation was published in an online article Charted: The Rapid Decline in Global Birth Rates. The objective of the article, and therefore the data visualisation, was to demonstrate the shrinking birth rates across the globe to its audience.

Audience The company that published the article, Visual Capitalist, is an online publisher that focuses on providing data visualisations on topics like markets, technology,energy and the global economy (Visual Capitalist, n.d). Its target audience are individuals within the investing community, in particular, company executives and other decision markers. For this particular data visualisation, it would have been intended for investors interested in healthcare, automation and the silver beauty industries as it highlights the change in demographics that the world is facing (Fidelity, 2023).

Improvements

The original data visualisation chosen could be improved in the three following ways:

  • First Improvement: Restricting the years to between 1965-2021. While the data on which the data visualisation is based is accurate, the visualisation is deceitful as it starts its visualisation from 1950. From the 1940s to mid 1960s there was a abnormal increase in birth rates, in what has more commonly become known as the Baby Boom (Bouk, 2018). Due to this, using data from this period, while providing a dramatic decrease in birth rates, is not an accurate depiction on the decline in birth rates. As such the year after the baby boom had finished, 1965, would be a more appropiate year to start the data visual.

  • Second Improvement: Increasing the amount of countries visualised. The second improvement required is to increase the number of locations from the original 49 to 347 different locations. The original countries were chosen as they were the most populous countries of 2021. However due to this, the countries were mainly from Asia and Africa. There were also no countries from the Oceania region. As such it is not an accurate depiction of global birth rates as per its objective.

  • Third Improvement: Changing the faceted line graph to a faceted choropleth. The original visualisation complicated the comparison between the 49 different line graphs as there were too many to view at once. As the number of countries being visualised is being increased, having faceted line graphs is no longer practical. For ease of the viewer, the graph will be changed to a faceted choropleth that will depict the birth rate in 1965 and 2021. This will allow the viewer to compare the differences between global birth rates without having to continuously scroll between each country.

# Filtering dataset for required variables of Location Name, ISO3-Alpha Code, Location Type, Years and Crude birth Rate
birth_data<-WPP2024_GEN_F01_DEMOGRAPHIC_INDICATORS_COMPACT_1_%>%select(3,6,9,11,26)
# Selecting for observations in the years 1965 and 2021, and with the Location Type Country/Area.
birth_data_years<-birth_data%>%filter(Year %in% c(1965,2021), Type %in% c("Country/Area"))

# Renaming variable "Crude Birth Rate(births per 1,000 population)" to "Births per 1,000 people"
colnames(birth_data_years)[5]<-"Births"

#creating map
world<-ne_countries(scale='medium',returnclass = 'sf')
world_birth1<-left_join(world,birth_data_years, by = c("iso_a3"="ISO3 Alpha-code"))
world_birth2<-world_birth1%>% filter(!is.na(Year))
faceted_smap<-ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data=world_birth2, aes(fill= Births)) +
  ggtitle("Global Crude Birth Rates for 1965 and 2021") +
  labs(fill="Birth Rates per 1,000",
       caption = "Data: United Nations World Population Prospects 2024")+
  facet_wrap(~Year, ncol = 2)+
  scale_y_continuous((breaks=seq(0, 50, by=10)))+
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours = sf.colors(7))+
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "white"),
          plot.title = element_text(size=20))
